<br>
 <br>
1. Only experienced and able role-players are allowed in this RPG. If you have never role-played before, or don’t consider yourself a good writer, then don’t join. If you’re unsure, or think that you could do a good job, then contact a member of the staff and ask them what they think.<br>
<br>
2. Always use third person when you post In Character. This helps things flow well, and makes it easier to understand what your character is doing.<br>
<br>
3. Do not use asterisks (*) at the beginning and end of each In Character post. If you need to separate actions and dialogue, do so by placing appropriate space between them, or use a different type of font. (Italicized, bold, different colors, etc.)<br>
<br>
4. Use detail in your posts! Explain what your character is thinking, how he/she is feeling, and their actions. Talk about the weather, the setting, EVERYTHING! There is absolutely no reason to make a one-line post in character. Make your posts worth something and put work into them.<br>
<br>
5. No god-moding. This means that your character is not invincible. Everyone has weaknesses; no exceptions. This also means that your character cannot do things that are not realistic. For example, no student can perform an Unforgivable Curse. No first year can do magic that Harry did in his fourth year.<br>
<br>
6. Characters cannot have access to information that they wouldn’t normally have. If you just made up a character, he/she cannot know the truth about Sirus Black, or know that Snape was once a Death Eater. Be realistic.<br>
<br>
7. No killing/maiming another person’s character without their permission. People work hard to develop their characters. It’s fine if you both discuss it and agree to kill off a character; but you must have permission.<br>
<br>
8. Use common sense. This RPG takes place during Harry’s fifth year, after the events in The Goblet of Fire. <br>
